f society and that this occurs if these systems resonate with members` conscious and unconscious beliefs and desires or are employed by them as a resource for the construction of defense mechanisms. He compares his firsthand observations of a Burmese village to extensive data from a wide array of other societies (including our own) and argues that this explanation applies to all societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aEthnopsychologyzBurma. 0aGender identityzBurma. 0aInterpersonal relationszBurma. 0aSex rolezBurma. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aFoer, Franklin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package Archivez978311053801440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300146554423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300146554.jpg  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook Package Archive  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles